*****
[4] West Virginia
Date: Mon 9 Nov 2015
Source: WTOV9 [edited]
http://wtov9.com/news/local/whooping-cough-cases-up-in-west-virginia


There have been 52 confirmed cases of pertussis, or whooping cough, so far in 2015 in West Virginia, and health officials confirm 5 outbreaks of the disease. It's a disease that can be stopped [prevented] with a vaccine.

"When an outbreak occurs, we move quickly to quash that because if not, we can have an entire day care, school or community affected very quickly," Howard Gamble of the Wheeling-Ohio County Health Department said, "When you have an outbreak announced concerning public health, you become a little more vigilant. We put out notices to hospitals and doctors that says be on the lookout for Pertussis. We're seeing it our area or different parts of the state. Now is the time to be [cognizant] of what's going on."

Gamble says Ohio County is not 1 of the 5 counties, but 1 county in the Ohio Valley has been affected, so all 55 counties are on alert. The 5 counties have not been revealed by state administrators, but Gamble says it is a serious, but preventable, issue. Gamble added whooping cough was a big deal back in the 1920s, when more than 100 000 people contracted the disease and more than 500 died from it. He says as living conditions improved and access to health care was easier, the numbers dwindled.

[Byline: Crissy Clutter]

